post_text: The Wallowa School District teachers are committed to quality instruction for students. Elementary teachers ensure 110 minutes of core reading instruction each day. Here students engage with literacy skills such as phonics, phonemic awareness, and spelling. Students practice rhyming, short vowels, and initial consonant sounds. They engage with the core reading adoption, Reading Street, and the Words Their Way program. Quality core reading instruction is key in the Response to Intervention (RTI) model and a reason our students learn at high levels! Students participating in distance learning are also engaged in this learning.

post_text: The superintendents of Wallowa County school districts, wish to acknowledge the efforts of a stakeholder group that resulted in the creation of relevant metrics for opening remote, rural and small school districts to in-person instruction this fall. Included in that group were our colleagues, healthcare providers, Wallowa and Union County Commissioners, our state senators and representatives, health care providers and representatives from the Oregon Department of Education, Oregon Health Authority and the Governor’s office. Those in this group accomplished a tremendous task in a very short period of time. In particular, Representative Mark Owens and Union County Commissioner Paul Anderes played a huge role in initiating and informing the work – special thanks to each of you. The newly published exceptions to the state-level reopening metrics are appropriate and provide for the health and safety of both students and community members alike. Many thanks to each of you for giving your time and energy to safety and education in Wallowa County.

post_text: PSA for Wallowa County parents... someone has created an anonymous snapchat account called WC Tea that is being used for kids to anonymously bash on and bully other kids. The posts are cruel, some kids are being targeted by groups of kids. The account owner is receiving these comments, blurring out the sender's name and posting them. Would be great if it got shut down, not what our kids need right now. This was brought to my attention by a parent and her kids have reported the account and encouraged their friends not to participate, but just wanted to let parents know! Check in with your kiddos and hopefully it gets shut down! -I haven’t seen the account only heard of it. Everyone should know and talk to their kids!!

post_text: Graduation is this Saturday, May 23, 2020 11:00 AM at the Wallowa Nez Perce Homeland Grounds. Please follow parking guidelines and remain in your vehicles. Congratulations to our Graduating Seniors!
text: Graduation is this Saturday, May 23, 2020 11:00 AM at the Wallowa Nez Perce Homeland Grounds. Please follow parking guidelines and remain in your vehicles. Congratulations to our Graduating Seniors!

post_text:
Senior Quinten Tillery

It is sad to say it is over but it is also a great relief. It is our way of growing up and starting a life of our own, to become responsible adults. Life with my class of 2020 has been one to remember. Most of us have been together since the day we walked into Pre-School. My class is another family that I will not forget. We have so many memories together that will never be replaced. We’ve always stuck together. Always had each other’s backs even though school got hard sometimes. Drama, violence, and bullying, it’s all part of high school but this is the time that we leave all that behind. The time to move forward with our lives and focus on the future of being an adult. After high school I plan to attend Eastern Oregon University and major in Chemistry. I hope to see the rest of my class be successful and responsible adults. It’s time to move forward and let go of the past. Peace out 2020!

Wallowa County Glass artist Stirling Webb, of Moonshine Glass in Enterprise, is crafting special mementos of this very different graduation for the seniors and faculty of each of our school districts. Outlaws will receive a glass cowboy hat. Joseph Eagles well be awarded a glass feather with their diploma, and Cougars will receive a glass cougar paw. The project is generously supported by the Enterprise Animal Clinic, Center for Wellness, the staff of Winding Waters Community Health Center, Main Street Motors, and Wallowa County Grain Growers. Here's an 11 minute video of Stirling and his assistant Jake Kurtz producing one of the Outlaw cowboy hats.

In honor of our senior students, all Wallowa County High Schools will be turning on their football lights as a symbol of hope and support for all Wallowa County students beginning on Monday 4/13/2020.

We want all of our students and especially our seniors to know how important they are to us and we care for each and every one of them.

The lights will come on every Monday through the end of the school year at 20:20 military time in honor of our seniors (8:20 pm) and will light up the stadium for one minute of each school day lost during this pandemic.

Dear Wallowa Families,

Due to circumstances beyond our control, we will be unable to offer the level of instruction we had hoped to provide.
K-6 materials will still be available for pick-up today in the BJR from 12 – 6. The materials provided are recommended but not mandatory.

Grades 7-12 formal assignments will be on hold at this time. We encourage students to utilize resources to continue their education on their own.

Enjoy your extended family time and we will be in contact with you as we learn more.

Thank you for your continued support.

post_text:
Governor Kate Brown has announced a statewide school closure for students in Oregon from Monday, March 16 through Tuesday, March 31. We will plan for students to return on Wednesday, April 1, 2020.

Our staff is working on a process to push out education to students who will be required to continue completing school work. They will not be given school work during their regular spring break March 23-27.

We are required to provide nutrition services. This will be in the form of a drive up service. We will let you know as soon as possible what this looks like.

We will post updates as they are available on the Wallowa School District Facebook page and remain in communication by phone and email.

If you are not contacted by noon today by the school, please call to provide your email and information about your availability of internet and a computer or device. Thank you.

Wallowa County Chieftain
March 11 at 11:01 PM ·

Donkey Basketball at Wallowa tonight. A truely fun event and fundraiser, in which boys and girls teams participated, aboard tame, docile, donkeys supplied and bred by Donkey Sports, Inc. of Entiat, Washington. These donkeys are basketball pros, and tour Oregon, Washington, and Idaho doing fundraisers. They don't quite wear Nikes or Converse, but instead "wear" soft rubber boot heels instead of conventional shoes or Easy Boots, according to their "manager and coach", Jeff Pittsinger of Donkey Sports, Inc. After tonight's game they were supposed to go to Halfway, but are, instead headed to Idaho because Halfway canceled its game as part of COVID-19 prevention. Rules require, among other things, that to retrieve a loose ball, you have to get off your donkey, and "lead" the donkey while you get the ball. They also require that the donkeys just walk, which they are happy to do. Do NOT miss Donkey Basketball next year!

post_text:
Parents for grades 7th-12th should have received a letter in the mail with instructions for how to access their student's grades and information.

Students in grades 7th-12th received information at school this week to set up their own accounts.

We now use a system called Synergy. The parent app is called ParentVue and the Students have their own accounts with StudentVue. You can access both these systems online or you can download an app on your phone.

The School Website has a link within the "Useful Links" box on the right side of the home page: http://www.wallowa.k12.or.us/

or you can use this website:
https://or-wal.edupoint.com/PXP2_Login.aspx

You will need an activation code provided from the school to set up an account. If you did not receive this in the mail or for questions, call the HS office at (541)886-2951.

Sports physicals Information
Students who participate in extracurricular sports in grades 7-12 are required to have a psychical examination once every two years. 5th and 6th graders participating in a junior high sport must also have a physical.

The forms can be found at:
http://www.osaa.org/docs/forms/PhysicalExamination-English2017.pdf
